Here is the commit message:
PlaintextPasswordEncoder ignores null encoded passwords

Fixes gh-7023

Here is the root cause:
The `isPasswordValid` method in the `PlaintextPasswordEncoder` class did not check for `null` values for the `encPass` parameter, which could lead to unexpected behavior or errors when attempting to validate a password against a null encoded password. This oversight allowed the method to proceed with a null value, potentially causing issues in the authentication process.

Here is the patch:

 	public boolean isPasswordValid(String encPass, String rawPass, Object salt) {
+		if (encPass == null) {
+			return false;
+		}
 		String pass1 = encPass + "";

 		// Strict delimiters is false because pass2 never persisted anywhere
 		// and we want to avoid unnecessary exceptions as a result (the
 		// authentication will fail as the encodePassword never allows them)
 		String pass2 = mergePasswordAndSalt(rawPass, salt, false);

 		if (ignorePasswordCase) {
 			// Note: per String javadoc to get correct results for Locale insensitive, use
 			// English
 			pass1 = pass1.toLowerCase(Locale.ENGLISH);
 			pass2 = pass2.toLowerCase(Locale.ENGLISH);
 		}
 		return PasswordEncoderUtils.equals(pass1, pass2);
 	}



